## Per-Spec Negotiation

Within the NEGOTIATING_SPECS stage, each specification item is negotiated independently. Each `SpecNegotiation` record tracks one spec item and has its own status lifecycle.

### Spec item statuses

```
PENDING
  ↓ (either party counters)
COUNTERED
  ↓ (counterparty accepts)        ↓ (counterparty rejects)       ↓ (either party locks)
AGREED                          REJECTED                   FINAL_OFFER_PENDING
                                                                 ↓           ↓
                                                          FINAL_OFFER_    FINAL_OFFER_
                                                           ACCEPTED        REJECTED
```

### Final-offer grim trigger

When a party issues a final offer on a spec item, the item enters `FINAL_OFFER_PENDING`. The counterparty can only accept or reject — no further counter is possible. If rejected, the entire negotiation fails. This is a credible commitment device: it gives each party one opportunity to draw a firm line, with the consequence of failure as enforcement.

Hard-constraint specs (`SpecType.HARD_CONSTRAINT`) follow the same flow but are flagged at creation — if the buyer's hard constraint cannot be met, the system can infer this as the primary failure cause.

### Spec actions recorded

Every action on every spec item creates a `SpecNegotiationHistory` record: `INITIAL`, `ACCEPT`, `COUNTER`, `REJECT`, `DELETE`, `FINAL_OFFER`, `FINAL_ACCEPT`, `FINAL_REJECT`, `HC_ACCEPT`, `HC_REJECT`.

