## Turn Tracking

Turn enforcement ensures that only the party whose turn it is can take action. A party cannot act twice in a row.

### Fields (on `Inquiry` model)

```
specNegotiationTurn      String   — userId of the party whose turn it is
specNegotiationTurnRole  String   — "buyer" | "seller"
priceNegotiationTurn     String   — same, for price stage
priceNegotiationTurnRole String
```

Per-dimension fields in `PriceNegotiation`:

```
priceAwaitingRole         String
paymentModeAwaitingRole   String
quantityAwaitingRole      String
leadTimeAwaitingRole      String
```

Each escrow tranche (`EscrowTranche`) also has its own `awaitingRole` field.

### Flip mechanism

`validateAndTransferTurn(inquiryId, actorId, actorRole)` in `negotiationOrchestrator.ts`:

1. Reads current `specNegotiationTurn` from `Inquiry`
2. Asserts `actorId === specNegotiationTurn` — throws HTTP 403 if not
3. Atomically updates `specNegotiationTurn` to the counterparty's userId and `specNegotiationTurnRole` to the counterparty's role
4. All within the same Prisma transaction as the state mutation

### RFQ exception

Turn enforcement is suppressed for the SPECS and PRICE stages on RFQ-sourced inquiries (`Inquiry.rfqBidId` is set). Only the CONTRACT stage enforces turn order for RFQ deals. This reflects the different negotiation dynamic of a competitive bid response versus a bilateral negotiation.

